  "prompt": "Does more effective mass mean more mass? If yes, because graphene has infinite effective mass, has it infinite mass as well?",
  "response": "Let me clarify this carefully:\n\n1. Effective mass is NOT the same as actual mass:\n- Effective mass is a concept in solid-state physics describing how a particle behaves in a crystal's periodic potential\n- It's a way to simplify complex quantum mechanical interactions\n- It can be different from real mass and can even be negative or infinite in special conditions\n\n2. For graphene specifically:\n- Its electrons behave as if they have zero rest mass but \"infinite\" effective mass near certain points\n- This doesn't mean the electrons actually have infinite real mass\n- It's a consequence of the unique electronic band structure of graphene\n\n3. Practical interpretation:\n- \"Infinite\" effective mass means electrons behave differently near specific energy/momentum points\n- It doesn't translate to infinite real mass\n- The actual mass of graphene's electrons remains unchanged\n\nSo to directly answer your questions:\n- More effective mass does NOT necessarily mean more real mass\n- Graphene's \"infinite\" effective mass does NOT mean infinite actual mass\n\nThe effective mass is a mathematical tool to understand electron behavior, not a literal description of mass.",
